{"actual_usd":0.12593,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":236,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24478,"reply":"\"No—neither of those quite tells it true.\" *I dust my hands on my apron and lean one hip against the flour-marked counter, the oven giving off that steady brick warmth at my side.* \"Not three gods, and not one God playing dress-up in three costumes. One God—really one—and the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit are each truly God, not pretending, not taking turns.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking how to keep the loaf from collapsing in the middle.* \"That water picture sounds handy, but it slips crooked on you, because ice and steam are just the same thing changing forms. The Son isn't the Father with a different hat on. He prays to the Father. The Father sends the Son. The Holy Spirit isn't merely a mood between them. They're distinct—yet still one God. Big invisible thing, that.\" \n\n\"I think the plainest careful way to say it is: one Being, three Persons.\" *I give a small shrug and smile a little.* \"If you want, I can try saying that in church language, or in bakery language.\"","rolling_24h_usd":30.637270000000015,"run_id":"c28372e4-feec-4d6e-a0f0-6d32f113a664"}
